{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17413575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17413575"},"attributes":{"position":22,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T08:18:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T08:18:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492793"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1261100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1261100"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T07:52:04+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T10:28:52+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":62,"questionsAnswered":61,"marksTotal":61,"marksAttainable":61,"marksAttempted":61,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T09:15:31+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0.2,"questionsCorrect":12,"marksCorrect":12},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"1157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.57,0.26,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41661"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1157"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26582"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"1201"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2066"},{"type":"tags","id":"4092"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3028"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41661","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41661"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents with a three month history of episodic dull perineal pain, which radiates into his lower abdomen and scrotum. The symptoms occur about five times a week and may last for several hours. He also has some difficulty in passing urine, getting up once every night and being left with a sensation of incomplete emptying of his bladder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 67/min and blood pressure 130/85mmHg. Abdominal examination is unremarkable and his bladder is not palpable. His prostate gland is smooth, symmetrical, enlarged and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis investigation results are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: unremarkable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrine culture: negative\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProstate-specific antigen: 3.5 ng/ml (\u0026lt;4.0).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prostate massage and repeat urine culture","Transurethral prostatectomy","Tamsulosin","CT pelvis and abdomen","Transperineal prostate biopsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s clinical pictures most likely suggests he has a chronic pelvic pain syndrome (CPPS)/Chronic Prostatitis (CP) as supported by his ongoing perineal, lower abdominal and scrotal pains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECPPS/CP is a minimally understood condition, with an estimated prevalence of 8.4-25% across multiple countries . Diet (alcohol, spicy foods), lifestyle factors (high stress levels, sedentary) and perineal trauma may be potential risk factors for this presentation. Characteristic features of this syndrome include perineal and/or lower abdominal pain, urologic symptoms and sexual dysfunction; which typically persists for a minimum of three months. Patients may experience symptoms suggestive of bladder neck outflow obstruction. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinary infection must be excluded and urodynamic studies may be considered to exclude any voiding dysfunction. The clinical examination and investigation results show no alarming features that would warrant further investigation via \u003Cstrong\u003Ebiopsy, CT \u003C/strong\u003Eor\u003Cstrong\u003E surgical intervention (prostatectomy)\u003C/strong\u003E for a prostate malignancy. Moreover, with a non-tender prostate and negative \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine culture\u003C/strong\u003E, an infectious process appears less likely so repeat cultures may yield very little.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAs management of CPPS is primarily driven by symptomatic relief, \u003Cstrong\u003Etamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E (alpha blocker) willl provide some benefit for this patient. Other pharmacotherapy measures that may be considered for these patients include anti-inflammatory meds, neuropathic pain meds and 5 alpha-reductase inhibitors.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In patients with suspected chronic pelvic pain syndrome/chronic prostatitis it is important to exclude the presence of bacterial infection prior to commencing treatment.","Management of CPPS is primarily driven by symptomatic relief using medications such as tamsulosin (alpha blocker)."],"references":["Zhang J, Liang C, Shang X, Li H. Chronic Prostatitis/Chronic Pelvic Pain Syndrome: A Disease or Symptom? Current Perspectives on Diagnosis, Treatment, and Prognosis. Am J Mens Health. 2020;14(1). Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7256330/pdf/10.1177_1557988320903200.pdf","Smith CP. Male chronic pelvic pain: An update. Indian J Urol. 2016;32(1):34-39. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4756547/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26582"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26582"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-20T21:02:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-20T21:02:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1157"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41661"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suita